  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Philadelphia who grew up in a family where both parents had advanced degrees, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can cast a long shadow over young minds. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's the quiet anxiety that lingers when a student, especially a girl or someone from a minority background, knows their group is often portrayed as less capable in science and math. I remember when my daughter, now a college student, would hesitate to ask questions in her physics class because she felt like she was 'not good enough.' That moment made me realize how deeply these fears can take root. We absolutely must address stereotype threat in STEM, not just as an academic issue but as a matter of fairness and opportunity. The solution isn't about changing the curriculum alone; it's about creating classrooms where every child feels seen and valued. I've always believed in the power of community—my husband and I have been involved in local initiatives to support girls in STEM through after-school clubs and mentorship programs. By fostering environments where students can explore without fear of judgment, we can help break down these barriers. It's not about fixing students but about building confidence through encouragement and understanding. When we treat every child with the respect they deserve, we're not just addressing a problem—we're nurturing the next generation of innovators.",
